 to be based on the function. The reference response's poem uses terms like \"prev,\" \"current,\" \"next_node,\" and describes the reversal process. The sample poems also use these terms and relate the code to poetic imagery. So another criterion is whether the poem accurately reflects the function's logic.\n\nAnother point is whether the code is well-documented. The reference response has comments explaining each step, which is helpful. The sample responses also have comments, so checking for comments might be a criterion.\n\nThe poem should be creative and poetic. The reference and samples have different styles, but they all use metaphors related to the code. So a criterion could be if the poem uses appropriate poetic devices.\n\nThe code should be efficient. The reference uses an iterative approach which is O(n) time and O(1) space. The sample responses also use similar methods, so checking for efficiency is important.\n\nThe poem should be self-contained, not relying on external references. The samples have standalone poems, so that's a criterion.\n\nThe code should be properly formatted with correct syntax. The reference and samples have correct Python syntax, so checking for syntax correctness is needed.\n\nLastly, the poem should be relevant to the linked list reversal. The samples all tie the poem to the code's functionality, so ensuring relevance is another criterion.\n\nNow, I need to make sure each criterion is specific to the task, binary (yes/no), and not vague. Let me list them out:\n\n1. Instruction Following: Code correctly reverses the linked list.\n2. Poem Relevance: Poem accurately reflects the function's logic.\n3. Code Documentation: Code includes comments explaining each step.\n4. Poetic Creativity: Poem uses appropriate metaphors and poetic devices.\n5. Code Efficiency: Code uses an efficient algorithm (iterative, O(n) time).\n6. Self-Contained Poem: Poem is standalone without external references.\n7. Code Syntax: Code is correctly formatted 